ODE VI.

‘Hercle exploits require a Homer to sing cf thern.’ says Horace, and so gives Agrippa the lyric glory that (it would seem) he has asked for, while professing to leave the task of celebrating such exploits to the epic genius of Varius. For panegyric cast in the same form compare Od. a. 12 and 4. a.

The Ode is addressed to M. Vipsanius Agrippa, me friend and connsellor of Augustus, and the greatest commender of his reign. He finally defeated Sextus Pompeius at Naulochos in tac. 36, and commanded at Actium in ac. 31. After the death of Marcellus (and consequently‚ it would seem. after the publication cf this Ode) he was married by Augustus to his daughter Julia (uc. 21); was asso- ciated with him (rac.18) in the Tribunitian power, and was looked upon as his intended successor. He died four years before Horace. in uc. η.
